<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: IN POLITICS, GATES RUNS TRUE TO FORM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When Microsoft Corp. Chairman Bill Gates decided to back a Washington state 
legislative candidate who is married to one of his employees, he did it in 
typical fashion -- via electronic mail. 
</P>
<P>
 Sandra Jacobson sent Gates an e-mail note about her husband, Stu, a liberal 
Democrat running in Gates' home district. 
</P>
<P>
 "It sounds like we agree on many things," Gates wrote. "I am willing to 
endorse Stu. . . . Of course, I can't put any time into it but you can mention 
me as a supporter." 
</P>
<P>
 Steve Van Luven, Jacobson's Republican opponent, said of Gates' notes: "I 
don't think the public cares what he does." 
</P>
</TEXT>
