<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHINA LIMITS ATHLETE HURT IN CRACKDOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 China is barring an athlete from international games for the disabled because 
his legs were crushed by a tank during the bloody crackdown on the Tian An Men 
Square democracy movement, a friend said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Xu Liangying, a longtime democracy activist, said the authorities were afraid 
foreign reporters would start asking embarrassing human rights questions if 
they found out how the athlete, Fang Zheng, was disabled. 
</P>
<P>
 Fang's permission to compete in next week's competition in Beijing was 
canceled in July.  
</P>
<P>
 Fang was a senior at the Beijing Physical Education College when the capital 
was rocked by the huge student demonstrations for democracy in 1989. During the 
crackdown, Fang's legs were crushed under a tank. One of his legs was amputated 
at the knee, the other above the knee, Xu said. 
</P>
