<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: TOLUCA LAKE; CAFE OWNER ARRESTED AFTER THROWING FOOD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VIVIEN LOU CHEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Misdemeanor charges may be filed against a cafe owner who hurled a container 
of food at a health inspector and was later arrested and booked for battery, 
authorities said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Romelia Issakhanian, owner of the trendy Cafe du Soleil on Riverside Drive in 
Toluca Lake, had a belligerent history toward health officials, forcing the 
inspector to bring along a supervisor for protection, according to the county 
Department of Health Services. 
</P>
<P>
 "She apparently gets somewhat upset when health inspectors come by. It's not 
uncommon. It's uncommon when they get physical with our people," said Carl 
Charles, who oversees the agency's restaurant inspections. 
</P>
<P>
 Issakhanian, 41, declined to discuss the incident, but said: "I am not some 
criminal." 
</P>
<P>
 Inspector Bessie Gallanis and her supervisor, Grainne Clarke, found 22 safety 
violations during their unexpected visit Thursday, including the improper sale 
of turkey and chicken prepared at Issakhanian's Burbank home. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities said the cafe owner willingly threw most of it into the trash, but 
hurled a container of the food at Gallanis, hitting the inspector in the knee. 
Clarke said she and Gallanis fled to phone police. 
</P>
<P>
 County health officials said they expect to have misdemeanor charges related 
to the food violations filed against Issakhanian. The Burbank city attorney's 
office may also file a misdemeanor charge of battery, which is punishable by up 
to six months in jail, a maximum $2,000 fine, or both. 
</P>
<P>
 Clarke said the cafe owner has acted violently toward health officials three 
times before, but declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
 "The inspector was quite shaken by the whole situation," she said. "It was 
quite traumatic." VIVIEN LOU CHEN 
</P>
</TEXT>
