<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ALAMITOS; GOOD TIME, BAD POST FOR REALLY A SECRET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB MIESZERSKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Really A Secret, the fastest qualifier for tonight's $62,000 Gold Rush Derby 
at Los Alamitos, got the worst post for the 870-yard race. 
</P>
<P>
 Owned by Linda May Williams and trained by Dennis Givens, the 3-year-old drew 
the outside in the field of eight, meaning he figures to get caught wide. 
</P>
<P>
 Two of the other main contenders, Citation Five and Oh Oh The Signature, are 
directly inside Really A Secret. Thoroughbreds L.C. Tern and Tis A Little Doll, 
and Chicks Response, the three slowest qualifiers in the Gold Rush Derby trials 
on Aug. 19, drew the inside three posts. 
</P>
<P>
 Citation Five, beaten by a nose at 3-10 in his trial, is the most accomplished 
in the field. He has five victories in 17 starts and earnings of $61,097. 
</P>
<P>
 Two races later, Bein Cold Cash, who has four victories in six starts for 
trainer Blane Schvaneveldt, heads a field of 10 2-year-olds in the $12,000 
Santa Barbara Overnight Handicap at 350 yards. 
</P>
