<HEADLINE>
<P>
TITAN FORWARD LITTLE DISMISSED FROM SCHOOL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LON EUBANKS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Darren Little, a 6-7 forward who started 20 games last year for the Cal State 
Fullerton basketball team, has failed to meet the university's academic 
standards and has been dismissed from school. 
</P>
<P>
 Coach Brad Holland confirmed Friday that Little will be lost for his senior 
season because his grade-point average for the past academic year fell below 
university standards and he was not readmitted for the fall semester. 
</P>
<P>
 Little was the team's third leading scorer last season as a junior, averaging 
11.7 points. "Darren certainly was a potential starter for us this year," 
Holland said. "But we wish him well, and hope he goes back to school somewhere, 
and eventually can play one more year." 
</P>
<P>
 Little, who played in high school at Quitman, Ga., and at Palomar College in 
San Marcos, also was third on the team in rebounding. He shot 42.1% from the 
field and 56.1% on free throws. 
</P>
<P>
 This marks the second consecutive year that the Titans have lost a potential 
starter because of academic problems. Guard Don Leary also was declared 
ineligible last fall. 
</P>
